snippet.textDisplay:
I lost my Grandma almost 7 years ago to pancreatic cancer. I was 16. My whole life she had told me when I turn 16 she would take me to Italy and I feel so grateful to be able to say she kept that promise, even as sick as she was at the time. My mom told me after she passed that she told my Grandma at one of her chemo treatments that she didn't have to take me and that I would understand, but she wouldn't hear it. She refused to let her illness stop her from doing things she wanted to do. So she got on a plane with me and took me to Italy. My mom told me that my Grandma said she refused to let herself die on that trip because she didn't want to leave me with that memory. She died exactly 2 weeks to the day that we got back from Italy. But she kept her promise and made it one of the most amazing experiences of my life all while being so sick from battling pancreatic cancer.

I'm so incredibly proud of you two for this. It was so beautifully done and so inspiring. Your dad seemed like he was just about as good as they get. He would be so proud of you two.

snippet.textDisplay: I haven’t cried in years and I literally cried through this entire video. My heart goes out to you guys. Your dad sounds like he was an amazing father and role model to you both. I see you both putting pressure on yourselves to handle your grief as gracefully as he handled his battle through cancer. I just want you to know that what’s most important is that you be true to yourself and whatever you’re experiencing in any given moment. Your dad wouldn’t want you to be constantly comparing yourself to his greatness and feeling like you have to be just like him to make him proud. I’m sure he loved you for exactly who you are. You don’t have to handle your dad’s passing in the same way he handled dying of cancer. It doesn’t make you any less great if you allow yourself to express your full range of emotions about the situation. And in fact, because of your platform, you are able to help so many people finally give themselves permission to feel THEIR feelings because they see you being so vulnerable with yours. So thank you for sharing such an intimate journey with all of us, and please be gentle with yourselves. One of the most helpful things I learned from my therapist is that when we judge our emotions as bad or weak or inappropriate, etc. we add unnecessary suffering on top of whatever pain we may be experiencing. If we want to ease our suffering it is most helpful to VALIDATE our experience, such as “It makes a lot of sense that I’m having a hard time being there for my friends. My dad was my best friend and losing him has had a huge impact on me in a way that I can’t control. It’s ok if I feel or act differently than I did before he got sick and passed away. It’s ok if I have days where I don’t want to get out of bed or talk to anybody. I am not letting my dad down by allowing myself to be sad and grieve his passing, even if it makes me less available to the other people in my life for awhile.” 💖

snippet.textDisplay: i hate that the government has a cure for cancer but they do not want to give it out due to them wanting to decrease  the population. my uncle died last month due to brain cancer and i wasn’t that close with him but just to know someone that was all healthy go to not being able to feed himself, not being get up to go to the bathroom or do anything and sitting there watching him suffer without there being nothing we could do about it to him taking his last breath was something that didn’t seem real. he was healthy before cancer and then he started getting sicker and then he got better then his tumor came back and they even did 2 surgeries on him to get the tumor gone but it didn’t work, he always wore a beanie because he didn’t want people to see him without any hair and he got buried in his hat and glasses that he always wore. it’s crazy to me that i can go look at pictures of him when he first got diagnosed with cancer and he looked completed fine, but i can also remember what he looked like in his casket. he only had 3-6 months to live and they went by fast and it still feels like he’s alive and i just can’t see him but i know he’s gone for good and there’s nothing i can do about it. he also died at a young age.

snippet.textDisplay: This was so touching. Cancer is a truly evil disease, and i do not wish it upon anyone. On the 25th on this month, it will be 9 years since my dad passed away. I strongly believe in what the therapist said at the beginning, nobody grieves the same. My experience may have differed from yours, but one thing i can understand is that losing someone you love, who is close to your heart and who you care about is never easy. I wish you both, and your family the best in your path of grieving.
